Author: msn <msn@polaris.dev>
Date:   Wed Jun 10 16:17:54 2026 -0700

    I-perm-002 (#1196): semantic contraindication credit + structural negation guard + slate activation
    
    Behind PG_SWEEP_SEMANTIC_CONTRAINDICATION (default OFF -> byte-identical), the S0
    `contraindications` content requirement is satisfied by a contraindication DIRECTION signal, so a
    faithful warning whose source never uses the literal token still credits. The population token
    ("immunocompromised") stays the literal precision anchor. Both singular and plural concept tokens
    are relaxed.
    
    Three positive routes, all fail-closed against inversion (over-crediting a contraindication is
    §-1.1-lethal; under-crediting is a safe disclosed gap under always-release / I-perm-001):
      1. "not recommended" — UNLESS an "against" follows it anywhere downstream (the "recommend against"
         idiom inverts it; whole-tail scan, not a gameable fixed window).
      2. DIRECTIONAL IMPERATIVES ("should be avoided", "should/must not be used/given/administered").
      3. The bare concept STEM ("contraindicat...") — positive ONLY when NO negation context (pre OR
         post, within a tight 20-char window) surrounds ANY occurrence.
    
    Negative contractions are expanded first (aren't->are not, haven't->have not, shouldn't->should not;
    curly apostrophe normalized) so the guard is not defeated by spelling, plus "free of"/"devoid
    of"/"zero" absence forms.
    
    Codex diff-gate iterations (each a real over-credit P0, all fixed structurally):
      iter-1 P0: brittle contiguous negation list missed interposed qualifiers ("no known
        contraindications", "not generally/clearly contraindicated") -> windowed pre/post negation regex.
      iter-1 P2: whole-claim "are safe" scan under-credited a contrastive warning -> removed.
      iter-2 P0: contraction negations ("aren't contraindicated") bypassed the regex -> contraction
        normalization before matching.
      iter-3 P0: the "against" inverter interposed beyond the fixed 16-char window ("not recommended by
        the CDC source against use") -> whole-tail "against" scan for the recommend family.
      iter-3 P2: plural "contraindications" token not relaxed -> added to the concept set.
    
    Why the fix matters: the CDC source for `probiotic_immunocompromised_contraindication` says probiotics
    "should be avoided ... immunocompromised" — never "contraindicated". drb_76 claim 03-001 ("not
    recommended for patients who are immunocompromised", VERIFIED, cites the exact CDC url) genuinely
    WARNED yet went un-credited -> released_insufficient_safety_evidence. Proven on the saved drb_76 run:
    flag ON credits `contraindications` (coverage 2/5 -> 3/5), safety floor clears, the run flips to
    released_with_disclosed_gaps WITHOUT fabricating.
    
    Four independent guards stand between a claim and S0 credit: is_verified, exact canonical-source
    match, the literal population anchor, and this direction/negation guard.
    
    - native_gate_b_inputs.py: _expand_negative_contractions + _contraindication_direction_present
      (recommend/against route + imperatives + windowed stem-negation regex); _content_requirements_satisfied
      relaxes only the concept token.
    - d8_replay_harness.py: replay_release_outcome gains corpus_satisfaction passthrough (default False
      preserves the I-perm-009/I-perm-001 baseline bit-for-bit).
    - test_semantic_contraindication_iperm002.py: credit/refuse matrix incl. all Codex iter-1/2/3 P0/P2
      cases + plural token + the drb_76 behavioral flip (skipif saved pool absent).
    - run_gate_b.py: ACTIVATE PG_SWEEP_SEMANTIC_CONTRAINDICATION in the Gate-B slate (slate + required +
      force-on), fail-closed if an operator =0.
    
    Tests: 101 green (incl. all Codex iter-1/2/3 P0/P2 regressions + drb_76 flip); OFF byte-identical; 112 slate green.
    
    Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.8 (1M context) <noreply@anthropic.com>

